Even the senatorial provinces, as Asia and Africa, seem to feel the effects of the general irregularity⁸; and even the security of the frontier is said to be no longer fully maintained ⁹.

Some apparent taint of insanity seems to come in, completing and partly explaining the whole: perhaps traceable sometimes in the clear evidence of public documents-; as in the attempt, in his published auto- biography‚ to explain the condemnation of Seianus by a salsehood of childish transparency ¹⁰; or in the famous words preserved'of his letter to the senate, publishing to the world his agony of soul ¹¹! Again, at one time reproach seems to lacerate him ¹², at another he parades it1³ ; he hovers round and round Rome and never enters it 14; shifts his place restlessly in the last stage of decrepitude¹⁵. It is of little moment to decide be- tween various reports of his end, or to know exactly how the last few sands ran out of a life that to any good purpose had been extinct for years.

As a set off against the judgment of Tacitus has been often sought in the contemporary panegyric of Tiberius by Velleius ¹⁶, a few remarks upon it appear here necessary.
